<article>
  <h2>unsafeHTML &amp; Trusted Types: An Interactive Demo</h2>

  <p>
    This site demonstrates a security gap in Lit's <code>unsafeHTML</code> directive:
    it silently bypasses the browser's <strong>Trusted Types</strong> enforcement via
    Lit's internal <code>'lit-html'</code> policy — a no-op identity function that
    blesses any string as safe HTML.
  </p>

  <p>
    The demos walk through the problem step by step and present a proposed fix.
    Open DevTools to see what's happening in each demo.
  </p>

  <h3>Block 1: <code>unsafeHTML</code> (original directive)</h3>
  <ol>
    <li><a href="{{ '/pages/1-xss-risk/' | url }}"><strong>XSS Risk</strong></a> — raw string → alert fires.</li>
    <li><a href="{{ '/pages/2-manual-sanitization/' | url }}"><strong>DOMPurify</strong></a> — sanitized string → no alert, but nothing enforces it.</li>
    <li><a href="{{ '/pages/3-trusted-types-bypass/' | url }}"><strong>TT Bypass</strong></a> — TT on, raw string → alert fires anyway via Lit's internal policy.</li>
    <li><a href="{{ '/pages/4-trusted-html-breaks/' | url }}"><strong>TH Breaks</strong></a> — TT on, <code>TrustedHTML</code> → throws. <code>unsafeHTML()</code> rejects non-strings.</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Block 2: <code>unsafeHtmlTT</code> (modified directive)</h3>
  <ol start="5">
    <li><a href="{{ '/pages/5-unsafehtmltt-compat/' | url }}"><strong>TT: compat</strong></a> — no TT, raw string → alert fires (backward compat).</li>
    <li><a href="{{ '/pages/6-unsafehtmltt-dompurify/' | url }}"><strong>TT: sanitize</strong></a> — no TT, sanitized string → no alert.</li>
    <li><a href="{{ '/pages/7-unsafehtmltt-tt-string/' | url }}"><strong>TT: enforced</strong></a> — TT on, raw string → throws (correct).</li>
    <li><a href="{{ '/pages/8-unsafehtmltt-tt-dompurify/' | url }}"><strong>TT: fix</strong></a> — TT on, <code>TrustedHTML</code> → renders safely. The fix works.</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Key Code Locations</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>The no-op policy (the root cause):</strong><br>
      <code>lit-html.ts:263–267</code> — <code>trustedTypes.createPolicy('lit-html', { createHTML: (s) =&gt; s })</code>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>The original directive:</strong><br>
      <code>directives/unsafe-html.ts</code> — fake TemplateStringsArray path
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>The proposed fix:</strong><br>
      <code>directives/unsafe-html-tt.ts</code> — TrustedHTML path via <code>setHTMLUnsafe</code>
    </li>
  </ul>

